I89. Conditional permanent resident status for certain alien entrepreneurs, spouses, and children

I19(a) In general

I79(1) Conditional basis for status

I12Notwithstanding any other provision of this chapter, an alien entrepreneur (as defined in subsection (f)(1) of this section), alien spouse, and alien child (as defined in subsection (f)(2) of this section) shall be considered, at the time of obtaining the status of an alien lawfully admitted for permanent residence, to have obtained such status on a conditional basis subject to the provisions of this section.

I79(2) Notice of requirements

I18(A) At time of obtaining permanent residence

I13At the time an alien entrepreneur, alien spouse, or alien child obtains permanent resident status on a conditional basis under paragraph (1), the Attorney General shall provide for notice to such an entrepreneur, spouse, or child respecting the provisions of this section and the requirements of subsection (c)(1) of this section to have the conditional basis of such status removed.

I18(B) At time of required petition

I13In addition, the Attorney General shall attempt to provide notice to such an entrepreneur, spouse, or child, at or about the beginning of the 90-day period described in subsection (d)(2)(A) of this section, of the requirements of subsection (c)(1) of this section.

I18(C) Effect of failure to provide notice

I13The failure of the Attorney General to provide a notice under this paragraph shall not affect the enforcement of the provisions of this section with respect to such an entrepreneur, spouse, or child.

I19(b) Termination of status if finding that qualifying entrepreneurship improper

I79(1) In general

I12In the case of an alien entrepreneur with permanent resident status on a conditional basis under subsection (a) of this section, if the Attorney General determines, before the second anniversary of the alien's obtaining the status of lawful admission for permanent residence, that_

I13(A) the investment in the commercial enterprise was intended solely as a means of evading the immigration laws of the United States,

I13(B)(i) the alien did not invest, or was not actively in the process of investing, the requisite capital; or

I13(ii) the alien was not sustaining the actions described in clause (i) throughout the period of the alien's residence in the United States; or

I13(C) the alien was otherwise not conforming to the requirements of section 1153(b)(5) of this title,

Q04

I17then the Attorney General shall so notify the alien involved and, subject to paragraph (2), shall terminate the permanent resident status of the alien (and the alien spouse and alien child) involved as of the date of the determination.

I79(2) Hearing in removal proceeding

I12Any alien whose permanent resident status is terminated under paragraph (1) may request a review of such determination in a proceeding to remove the alien. In such proceeding, the burden of proof shall be on the Attorney General to establish, by a preponderance of the evidence, that a condition described in paragraph (1) is met.

I19(c) Requirements of timely petition and interview for removal of condition

I79(1) In general

I12In order for the conditional basis established under subsection (a) of this section for an alien entrepreneur, alien spouse, or alien child to be removed_

I13(A) the alien entrepreneur must submit to the Attorney General, during the period described in subsection (d)(2) of this section, a petition which requests the removal of such conditional basis and which states, under penalty of perjury, the facts and information described in subsection (d)(1) of this section, and

I13(B) in accordance with subsection (d)(3) of this section, the alien entrepreneur must appear for a personal interview before an officer or employee of the Service respecting the facts and information described in subsection (d)(1) of this section.

I79(2) Termination of permanent resident status for failure to file petition or have personal interview

I18(A) In general

I13In the case of an alien with permanent resident status on a conditional basis under subsection (a) of this section, if_

I14(i) no petition is filed with respect to the alien in accordance with the provisions of paragraph (1)(A), or

I14(ii) unless there is good cause shown, the alien entrepreneur fails to appear at the interview described in paragraph (1)(B) (if required under subsection (d)(3) of this section),

Q04

I32the Attorney General shall terminate the permanent resident status of the alien (and the alien's spouse and children if it was obtained on a conditional basis under this section or section 1186a of this title) as of the second anniversary of the alien's lawful admission for permanent residence.

I18(B) Hearing in removal proceeding

I13In any removal proceeding with respect to an alien whose permanent resident status is terminated under subparagraph (A), the burden of proof shall be on the alien to establish compliance with the conditions of paragraphs (1)(A) and (1)(B).

I79(3) Determination after petition and interview

I18(A) In general

I13If_

I14(i) a petition is filed in accordance with the provisions of paragraph (1)(A), and

I14(ii) the alien entrepreneur appears at any interview described in paragraph (1)(B),

Q04

I32the Attorney General shall make a determination, within 90 days of the date of the such filingÿ1A\1\N or interview (whichever is later), as to whether the facts and information described in subsection (d)(1) of this section and alleged in the petition are true with respect to the qualifying commercial enterprise.

