I79(2) Automated data sharing system

I18(A) System

I13The Attorney General and the Secretary of State shall develop and implement an automated data sharing system that will permit them to share data in electronic form from their respective records systems regarding the admissibility of aliens who are nationals of a program country.

I18(B) Requirements

I13The system under subparagraph (A) shall satisfy the following requirements:

I77(i) Supplying information to immigration officers conducting inspections at ports of entry

I14Not later than October 1, 2002, the system shall enable immigration officers conducting inspections at ports of entry under section 1225 of this title to obtain from the system, with respect to aliens seeking a waiver under the program_

I16(I) any photograph of the alien that may be contained in the records of the Department of State or the Service; and

I16(II) information on whether the alien has ever been determined to be ineligible to receive a visa or ineligible to be admitted to the United States.

I77(ii) Supplying photographs of inadmissible aliens

I14The system shall permit the Attorney General electronically to obtain any photograph contained in the records of the Secretary of State pertaining to an alien who is a national of a program country and has been determined to be ineligible to receive a visa.

I77(iii) Maintaining records on applications for admission

I14The system shall maintain, for a minimum of 10 years, information about each application for admission made by an alien seeking a waiver under the program, including the following:

I16(I) The name or Service identification number of each immigration officer conducting the inspection of the alien at the port of entry.

I16(II) Any information described in clause (i) that is obtained from the system by any such officer.

I16(III) The results of the application.

I79(3) Electronic travel authorization system

I18(A) System

I13The Secretary of Homeland Security, in consultation with the Secretary of State, shall develop and implement a fully automated electronic travel authorization system (referred to in this paragraph as the ``System'') to collect such biographical and other information as the Secretary of Homeland Security determines necessary to determine, in advance of travel, the eligibility of, and whether there exists a law enforcement or security risk in permitting, theÿ1A\4\N alien to travel to the United States.

I28N\4\ÿ1ASo in original. Probably should be ``an''.

I18(B) Fees

I77(i) In general

I14No later than 6 months after March 4, 2010, the Secretary of Homeland Security shall establish a fee for the use of the System and begin assessment and collection of that fee. The initial fee shall be the sum of_

I16(I) $10 per travel authorization; and

I16(II) an amount that will at least ensure recovery of the full costs of providing and administering the System, as determined by the Secretary.

I77(ii) Disposition of amounts collected

I14Amounts collected under clause (i)(I) shall be credited to the Travel Promotion Fund established by subsection (d) of section 2131 of title 22. Amounts collected under clause (i)(II) shall be transferred to the general fund of the Treasury and made available to pay the costs incurred to administer the System.

I77(iii) Sunset of Travel Promotion Fund fee

I14The Secretary may not collect the fee authorized by clause (i)(I) for fiscal years beginning after September 30, 2015.

I18(C) Validity

I77(i) Period

I14The Secretary of Homeland Security, in consultation with the Secretary of State, shall prescribe regulations that provide for a period, not to exceed three years, during which a determination of eligibility to travel under the program will be valid. Notwithstanding any other provision under this section, the Secretary of Homeland Security may revoke any such determination at any time and for any reason.

I77(ii) Limitation

I14A determination by the Secretary of Homeland Security that an alien is eligible to travel to the United States under the program is not a determination that the alien is admissible to the United States.

I77(iii) Not a determination of visa eligibility

I14A determination by the Secretary of Homeland Security that an alien who applied for authorization to travel to the United States through the System is not eligible to travel under the program is not a determination of eligibility for a visa to travel to the United States and shall not preclude the alien from applying for a visa.

I77(iv) Judicial review

I14Notwithstanding any other provision of law, no court shall have jurisdiction to review an eligibility determination under the System.

I18(D) Report

I13Not later than 60 days before publishing notice regarding the implementation of the System in the Federal Register, the Secretary of Homeland Security shall submit a report regarding the implementation of the system to_

I14(i) the Committee on Homeland Security of the House of Representatives;

I14(ii) the Committee on the Judiciary of the House of Representatives;

I14(iii) the Committee on Foreign Affairs of the House of Representatives;

I14(iv) the Permanent Select Committee on Intelligence of the House of Representatives;

I14(v) the Committee on Appropriations of the House of Representatives;

I14(vi) the Committee on Homeland Security and Governmental Affairs of the Senate;

I14(vii) the Committee on the Judiciary of the Senate;

I14(viii) the Committee on Foreign Relations of the Senate;

I14(ix) the Select Committee on Intelligence of the Senate; and

I14(x) the Committee on Appropriations of the Senate.

I19(i) Exit system

I79(1) In general

I12Not later than one year after August 3, 2007, the Secretary of Homeland Security shall establish an exit system that records the departure on a flight leaving the United States of every alien participating in the visa waiver program established under this section.

I79(2) System requirements

I12The system established under paragraph (1) shall_

I13(A) match biometric information of the alien against relevant watch lists and immigration information; and

I13(B) compare such biometric information against manifest information collected by air carriers on passengers departing the United States to confirm such aliens have departed the United States.

I79(3) Report

I12Not later than 180 days after August 3, 2007, the Secretary shall submit to Congress a report that describes_

I13(A) the progress made in developing and deploying the exit system established under this subsection; and

I13(B) the procedures by which the Secretary shall improve the method of calculating the rates of nonimmigrants who overstay their authorized period of stay in the United States.

