I32For purposes of clause (ii), an alien who has been convicted of an aggravated felony (or felonies) for which the alien has been sentenced to an aggregate term of imprisonment of at least 5 years shall be considered to have committed a particularly serious crime. The previous sentence shall not preclude the Attorney General from determining that, notwithstanding the length of sentence imposed, an alien has been convicted of a particularly serious crime. For purposes of clause (iv), an alien who is described in section 1227(a)(4)(B) of this title shall be considered to be an alien with respect to whom there are reasonable grounds for regarding as a danger to the security of the United States.

I18(C) Sustaining burden of proof; credibility determinations

I13In determining whether an alien has demonstrated that the alien's life or freedom would be threatened for a reason described in subparagraph (A), the trier of fact shall determine whether the alien has sustained the alien's burden of proof, and shall make credibility determinations, in the manner described in clauses (ii) and (iii) of section 1158(b)(1)(B) of this title.

I19(c) Removal of aliens arriving at port of entry

I79(1) Vessels and aircraft

I12An alien arriving at a port of entry of the United States who is ordered removed either without a hearing under section 1225(b)(1) or 1225(c) of this title or pursuant to proceedings under section 1229a of this title initiated at the time of such alien's arrival shall be removed immediately on a vessel or aircraft owned by the owner of the vessel or aircraft on which the alien arrived in the United States, unless_

I13(A) it is impracticable to remove the alien on one of those vessels or aircraft within a reasonable time, or

I13(B) the alien is a stowaway_

I14(i) who has been ordered removed in accordance with section 1225(a)(1) of this title,

I14(ii) who has requested asylum, and

I14(iii) whose application has not been adjudicated or whose asylum application has been denied but who has not exhausted all appeal rights.

I79(2) Stay of removal

I18(A) In general

I13The Attorney General may stay the removal of an alien under this subsection if the Attorney General decides that_

I14(i) immediate removal is not practicable or proper; or

I14(ii) the alien is needed to testify in the prosecution of a person for a violation of a law of the United States or of any State.

I18(B) Payment of detention costs

I13During the period an alien is detained because of a stay of removal under subparagraph (A)(ii), the Attorney General may pay from the appropriation ``Immigration and Naturalization Service_Salaries and Expenses''_

I14(i) the cost of maintenance of the alien; and

I14(ii) a witness fee of $1 a day.

I18(C) Release during stay

I13The Attorney General may release an alien whose removal is stayed under subparagraph (A)(ii) on_

I14(i) the alien's filing a bond of at least $500 with security approved by the Attorney General;

I14(ii) condition that the alien appear when required as a witness and for removal; and

I14(iii) other conditions the Attorney General may prescribe.

