I89. Protections for domestic workers and other nonimmigrants

I19(a) Information pamphlet and video for consular waiting rooms

I79(1) Development and distribution

I12The Secretary of State, in consultation with the Secretary of Homeland Security, the Attorney General, and the Secretary of Labor, shall develop an information pamphlet and video on legal rights and resources for aliens applying for employment- or education-based nonimmigrant visas. The video shall be distributed and shown in consular waiting rooms in embassies and consulates appropriate to the circumstances that are determined to have the greatest concentration of employment or education-based non-immigrant visa applicants, and where sufficient video facilities exist in waiting or other rooms where applicants wait or convene. The Secretary of State is authorized to augment video facilities in such consulates or embassies in order to fulfill the purposes of this section.

I79(2) Consultation

I12In developing the information pamphlet under paragraph (1), the Secretary of State shall consult with nongovernmental organizations with expertise on the legal rights of workers and victims of severe forms of trafficking in persons.

I19(b) Contents

I11The information pamphlet and video developed under subsection (a) shall include information concerning items such as_

I12(1) the nonimmigrant visa application processes, including information about the portability of employment;

I12(2) the legal rights of employment or education-based nonimmigrant visa holders under Federal immigration, labor, and employment law;

I12(3) the illegality of slavery, peonage, trafficking in persons, sexual assault, extortion, blackmail, and worker exploitation in the United States;

I12(4) the legal rights of immigrant victims of trafficking in persons and worker exploitation, including_

I13(A) the right of access to immigrant and labor rights groups;

I13(B) the right to seek redress in United States courts;

