I89. Posthumous citizenship through death while on active-duty service in armed forces during World War I, World War II, the Korean hostilities, the Vietnam hostilities, or in other periods of military hostilities

I19(a) Permitting granting of posthumous citizenship

I11Notwithstanding any other provision of this subchapter, the Secretary of Homeland Security shall provide, in accordance with this section, for the granting of posthumous citizenship at the time of death to a person described in subsection (b) of this section if the Secretary of Homeland Security approves an application for that posthumous citizenship under subsection (c) of this section.

I19(b) Noncitizens eligible for posthumous citizenship

I11A person referred to in subsection (a) of this section is a person who, while an alien or a noncitizen national of the United States_

I12(1) served honorably in an active-duty status in the military, air, or naval forces of the United States during any period described in the first sentence of section 1440(a) of this title,

I12(2) died as a result of injury or disease incurred in or aggravated by that service, and

I12(3) satisfied the requirements of clause (1) or (2) of the first sentence of section 1440(a) of this title.

Q04

I10The executive department under which the person so served shall determine whether the person satisfied the requirements of paragraphs (1) and (2).

I19(c) Requests for posthumous citizenship

I79(1) In general

I12A request for the granting of posthumous citizenship to a person described in subsection (b) of this section may be filed on behalf of that person_

I13(A) upon locating the next-of-kin, and if so requested by the next-of-kin, by the Secretary of Defense or the Secretary's designee with the Bureau of Citizenship and Immigration Services in the Department of Homeland Security immediately upon the death of that person; or

I13(B) by the next-of-kin.

I79(2) Approval

I12The Director of the Bureau of Citizenship and Immigration Services shall approve a request for posthumous citizenship filed by the next-of-kin in accordance with paragraph (1)(B) if_

I13(A) the request is filed not later than 2 years after_

I14(i) November 24, 2003; or

I14(ii) the date of the person's death;

Q04

I32whichever date is later;

I13(B) the request is accompanied by a duly authenticated certificate from the executive department under which the person served which states that the person satisfied the requirements of paragraphs (1) and (2) of subsection (b) of this section; and

I13(C) the Director finds that the person satisfied the requirement of subsection (b)(3) of this section.

I19(d) Documentation of posthumous citizenship

I11If the Director of the Bureau of Citizenship and Immigration Services approves the request referred to in subsection (c) of this section, the Director shall send to the next-of-kin of the person who is granted citizenship, a suitable document which states that the United States considers the person to have been a citizen of the United States at the time of the person's death.

